<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900802-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>900802-0028.</DOCID><HL>   GAO Faults System Used   To Fight Bank, Sandamp;L Crime</HL><DATE>08/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><IN>BANKS (BNK)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The General Accounting Office said theJustice Department doesn't have the kind of informationsystem its new financial-institutions fraud chief needs &quot;toeffectively oversee and coordinate&quot; the government's attackon thrift and bank crimes.   The GAO told the Senate Banking Committee it sees &quot;strongindications&quot; that the department is &quot;gearing up and deployingresources for increased effort against financial-institutionfraud.&quot; But the GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, saidthe department doesn't have a system to track bank and thriftfraud cases, &quot;how well the efforts are proceeding, what moreneeds to be done, where it needs to be done, and what furtherresources are actually needed.</LP><TEXT>   In fact, James Richmond, the department's special counselfor financial-institution fraud, has expressed frustrationover his inability to provide precise statistics on thestatus and number of major cases being handled by regionalU.S. attorneys' offices. Such information is crucial inmaking decisions about where to send additional resources. Ingeneral, the Justice Department has moved slowly towardcreating case-management systems, which use computers totrack the status of cases.</TEXT></DOC>